ard Upton于1331年出生在英国可瓦爾利斯可亞爾德时，他的父亲John Edward Upton31岁，母亲Elizabeth St. Winnow23岁。他于大约1355年与Agnes Carnother结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世于1398年在英国可瓦爾厄普頓享年67岁。"},"hr":{"1331–1398":"1331.–1398.","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1356–1450":"1356–1450","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1308–1368":"1308–1368.","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1368":"1368.","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1398":"1398.","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1331":"1331.","ABT 1355":"oko 1355.","about 1356":"oko 1356.","1308":"1308","Upton, Cornwall, England":"Upton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Liskeard, Cornwall, England":"Liskeard, Cornwall, England"},"cs":{"1331–1398":"1331–1398","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1356–1450":"1356–1450","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1308–1368":"1308–1368","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","ABT 1355":"okolo 1355","about 1356":"okolo 1356","1308":"1308","Upton, Cornwall, England":"Upton, Cornwall, Anglie","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Anglie","Liskeard, Cornwall, England":"Liskeard, Cornwall, Anglie"},"da":{"1331–1398":"1331–1398","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1356–1450":"1356–1450","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1308–1368":"1308–1368","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","ABT 1355":"omkring 1355","about 1356":"omkring 1356","1308":"1308","Upton, Cornwall, England":"Upton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Liskeard, Cornwall, England":"Liskeard, Cornwall, England"},"nl":{"1331–1398":"1331–1398","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1356–1450":"1356–1450","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1308–1368":"1308–1368","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","ABT 1355":"circa 1355","about 1356":"circa 1356","1308":"1308","Upton, Cornwall, England":"Upton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Liskeard, Cornwall, England":"Liskeard, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1331–1398":"1331–1398","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1356–1450":"1356–1450","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1308–1368":"1308–1368","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","ABT 1355":"about 1355","about 1356":"about 1356","1308":"1308","Upton, Cornwall, England":"Upton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Liskeard, Cornwall, England":"Liskeard, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Upton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in England called Upton, most of which are named with Old English <i>upp</i> ‘upper’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different origins, such as one in Essex, originally named with the phrase <i>upp in tūne</i> ‘up in the settlement’, i.e. the higher part of the settlement, and Upton Lovell (Wiltshire), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ubba</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>. This name was brought to Ireland (Antrim) in 1598 by Henry <i>Upton</i>, from Upton in Devon."],"variants":[{"name":"Uptain","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Upton  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":6,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":51,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Upton was born in 1331, in Liskeard, Cornwall, England, his father, John Edward Upton, was 31 and his mother, Elizabeth St. Winnow, was 23. He married Agnes Carnother abo